; Level data tables.

[Level:terrainProfiles:Terrain profiles]
The game defines 15 river bank shape profiles, each 16 bytes long (one byte
per scanline within a terrain fragment). Each byte is the X offset for the
left bank edge at that line. The right bank is computed as a mirror.

Profiles 1-2 have bit 7 set, which triggers special bridge/road rendering
in #R$6AA3.

#TABLE(default)
{ =h Profile | =h Type | =h Description }
{ 0          | Normal  | Standard river section }
{ 1          | Special | Pre-bridge approach (bit 7 set) }
{ 2          | Special | Bridge structure (bit 7 set) }
{ 3          | Normal  | Post-bridge transition }
{ 4-10       | Normal  | Various river widths }
{ 11         | Narrow  | River narrows significantly }
{ 12         | Wide    | River widens significantly }
{ 13-14      | Normal  | Additional variations }
TABLE#

Profile data: #R$8063 (240 bytes total).

[Level:islands:Island shapes]
36 island shape definitions, each 3 bytes. Islands appear as terrain features
within the river, splitting it into channels.

#TABLE(default)
{ =h Byte | =h Contents }
{ 0       | Profile index (0-14): selects shape from #R$8063 }
{ 1       | Width offset: shifts edge position }
{ 2       | Edge mode: 0=direct, 1=mirror (right = 120 - left), 2=fixed-width (right = 60 + left) }
TABLE#

Island data: #R$C600 (108 bytes total). Referenced from terrain fragment
byte 3 (upper 6 bits = island index × 4). Initialized by #R$696B.

[Level:terrainFragments:Terrain fragments]
Each of the 48 game levels (bridge sections) is defined by 64 terrain
fragments, stored as 4 bytes each (256 bytes per level). Fragments are loaded
sequentially by #R$6A4F as the terrain scrolls.

#TABLE(default)
{ =h Byte | =h Contents }
{ 0       | Profile (0-14): index into terrain profiles at #R$8063. Values 1-3 mark bridge approach, bridge, and post-bridge }
{ 1-2     | Row offset (16-bit): shifts bank position horizontally }
{ 3       | Bits 0-1: edge mode. Bits 2-7: island index (divide by 4 for #R$C600 lookup) }
TABLE#

Terrain data: #R$9500 (48 levels × 256 bytes = 12,288 bytes).

[Level:objectSpawns:Object spawn tables]
Each level has 128 spawn slots (2 bytes each, 256 bytes per level) that define
which objects appear at each scroll position. Read by #R$6F80 during scroll.

#TABLE(default)
{ =h Byte | =h Contents }
{ 0       | Object definition: bits 0-2 = type (<code>OBJECT_*</code> constants), bit 3 = rock flag (<code>SLOT_BIT_ROCK</code>) }
{ 1       | X position (<code>$00</code> = empty slot, <code>$01</code>–<code>$FF</code> = spawn coordinate) }
TABLE#

When the rock flag is set, bits 0-1 select rock variant (0-3). Most slots are
empty (X = <code>$00</code>), making this a sparse encoding.

Object data: #R$C800 (48 levels × 256 bytes = 12,288 bytes).
